<div class="tool-seo">
  <h2>What is a Hash Function?</h2>
  <p>A hash function takes input data of any size and produces a fixed-length output (the hash or digest). It's a one-way function — you can't reverse a hash back to the original input. Hash functions are fundamental to cryptography, data integrity verification, and password storage.</p>

  <h2>MD5 vs SHA-256 vs SHA-512</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>MD5</strong> — 128-bit hash. Fast but cryptographically broken. Use only for non-security purposes like file checksums.</li>
    <li><strong>SHA-1</strong> — 160-bit hash. Also broken for collision resistance. Deprecated for security use.</li>
    <li><strong>SHA-256</strong> — 256-bit hash. Part of SHA-2 family. Standard for TLS certificates, blockchain, and most security applications.</li>
    <li><strong>SHA-512</strong> — 512-bit hash. Part of SHA-2 family. More resistant to brute force, slightly slower. Used where maximum security is needed.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common Uses</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>File integrity</strong> — Verify downloads by comparing hash values</li>
    <li><strong>Password storage</strong> — Store hashed passwords instead of plaintext (always use salt + bcrypt/argon2 for passwords)</li>
    <li><strong>Git</strong> — Uses SHA-1 for commit identifiers</li>
    <li><strong>Blockchain</strong> — Bitcoin uses SHA-256, Ethereum uses Keccak-256</li>
    <li><strong>Digital signatures</strong> — Hash the document first, then sign the hash</li>
  </ul>
</div>

